Badbyte

Target IP: 10.10.238.247

Infiltrate BadByte and help us to take over root.

Scanning


There are two TCP ports open on the target machine: SSH and FTP. The FTP application allows anonymous login. I will start enumeration with this application.

Enumeration

Port 30024: FTP

This application allows anonymous login. I successfully connected to the target machine and downloaded the two files: id_rsa and note.txt on my machine.


The note.txt file contains the message above. There is a possible username called errorcauser. Maybe the SSH key belongs to this user?


The SSH key is encrypted. I used ssh2john to obtain the passphrase of this key. I got the password cupcake.

Port Forwarding & Further Enumeration


Using the command ssh -i id_rsa errorcauser@10.10.238.247, I successfully connected to the target machine using SSH. There is an interesting file called note.txt. This file contains the message above. It seems like there is another web application running internally which is not accessible by me. I will need to setup port forwarding. I used the command ssh -i id_rsa errorcauser@10.10.238.247 -D 1337 to setup the dynamic forwarding with SSH.


I added the change above in my /etc/proxychains.conf file.


Then I used the command proxychains nmap -sT 127.0.0.1 to perform a scan to identify possible open ports on the target machine. There are two TCP ports open internally: HTTP and MySQL.


I setup the port forwarding now. I should be able to access the web application from my machine now.


And bingo! I can now access the web application using port forwarding. The target host is running WordPress 5.7.



Using the command proxychains wpscan --url http://127.0.0.1:80 --plugins-detection aggressive, I performed a scan against the WordPress to identify any out-dated plugins with vulnerabilities. I found the plugin duplicator 1.3.26 is vulnerable to LFI.



The plugin wp-file-manager is also vulnerable to RCE. Before exploiting the target machine, I wish to enumerate further to find out the users of the system and see if I can obtain their SSH key using the LFI vulnerability.


By using the payload http://127.0.0.1/wp-admin/admin-ajax.php?action=duplicator_download&file=../../../../../../../../../etc/passwd, I managed to download the /etc/passwd file from the target machine. But I did not find anything else useful. Time to exploit the machine using the RCE.

Exploitation


I used the exploit module multi/http/wp_file_manager_rce from Metasploit to exploit the RCE vulnerability in wp-file-manager 6.0 plugin. The parameters I set are shown above for this exploit. But obviously, I started Metasploit using the command proxychains msfconsole -q . I used the payload payload/generic/shell_reverse_tcp as other payloads were not working for this exploit.


After firing the exploit, I have a reverse shell connection with the session as cth. Now I have a foothold on the target machine.

Privilege Escalation


Running the command find / -writable -type f 2>/dev/null shows an interesting entry called /var/log/bash.log. It contains the old password of the user cth. I sprayed this password against cth and root, but I had no luck.


However, spraying G00dP@$sw0rd2021 against the user cth worked! It looks like the user only changed the year from 2020 to 2021 -- which is not a secure password at all.


Game over. This user is able to run all commands with sudo. Now I have a root shell.
